            "loreEntryElements": [
                {
                    "@id": "/lore_entry_elements/01JBT1A5AGQEP3TZ22EY05WD3X",
                    "@type": "LoreEntryElement",
                    "id": "01JBT1A5AGQEP3TZ22EY05WD3X",
                    "loreEntryElementType": {
                        "@id": "/lore_entry_element_types/01GR6AENPX6HQP8G16KNV7BNA2",
                        "@type": "LoreEntryElementType",
                        "id": "01GR6AENPX6HQP8G16KNV7BNA2",
                        "reference": "FLAVOR_TEXT",
                        "subject": "Flavor Text"
                    },
                    "text": "Can you guess the secret ingredient? It's seasoned with Sap."
                },
                {
                    "@id": "/lore_entry_elements/01JBT1A5B052SVQV8CCY64171R",
                    "@type": "LoreEntryElement",
                    "id": "01JBT1A5B052SVQV8CCY64171R",
                    "loreEntryElementType": {
                        "@id": "/lore_entry_element_types/01GR6AE2ZSVVYP6SDJXN8Q5DVF",
                        "@type": "LoreEntryElementType",
                        "id": "01GR6AE2ZSVVYP6SDJXN8Q5DVF",
                        "reference": "STORY",
                        "subject": "Story"
                    },
                    "text": "Created by Hestia, Sap Stew (or fondue) is an original recipe made at the Mess incorporating the substance found in the City of Scholars. Sap is used as a flavor enhancer, giving sweet, savory, fragrant and floral notes to the dish. The ingredients are poached in the broth at mealtime.\n\nIngredients for 4 servings\n\n- Edamame-filled marumochi (12)\n- Martengale chashu (16 slices)\n- Bok choy (1)\n- Ngo gai (1 bunch)\n- Confit fiddleheads (8)\n- Cherry tomatoes (8)\n- Leek (1)\n- Kurudake (1)\n- Chopped garlic (2 cloves)\n- Minced shallot (1)\n- Minced fresh onion (1)\n- Fresh ginger (1 inch)\n- Soy sauce (1/2 cup)\n- Souma seed oil (1/4 cup)\n- Mirin (1 cup)\n- Sake (1 cup)\n- Sap (1 1/2 cups)\n- Powdered sugar (1/3 cup)\n- Dashi (1 cup)\n- Water\n- Rau ram\n- Cilantro\n- Red bird pepper \n- Recommended ideas: comfort, vividness, nostalgia for a summer night with friends, the nocturnal bloom of a jasmine flower, synesthetic resonance…\n\nInstructions\n\n- Preheat the oven to 410°F, then preheat the individual fondue pots for at least 30 minutes.\n- Wash the vegetables.\n- Add the soy sauce, mirin, sake, souma seed oil, dashi and Sap to a large saucepan. Mix in the sugar, fresh ginger, shallot, garlic and selected ideas. Cover with water, bring to a boil, and leave to simmer for 5 minutes. Remove the ginger.\n- Cook the marumochi in the broth for 10 minutes. When the edamame filling can be seen, the marumochi are ready. Set them aside.\n- Meanwhile, strip the leaves off the bok choy, ngo gai and rau ram. \n- Cut the chashu into approx. 1/2 inch slices.\n- Cut the kurudake into approx. 1/2 inch slices.\n- Slice the leeks diagonally into thin strips.\n- Remove the fondue pots from the oven and pour the broth inside.\n- In equal amounts, place the bok choy leaves, marumochi, chashu slices, kurudake, leek, cherry tomatoes, fiddleheads, and ngo gai.\n- Sprinkle with rau ram, bird pepper and cilantro.\n- Leave to simmer in the individual fondue pots, then enjoy.\n- Infuse the idea of heat if required."
                },
                {
